  }, "Ethan Zuckerman:")), mdx("p", null, "That thinking on public piece is something that I sort of miss from the golden age of blogging. I think we've gone through this transformation where a lot of bloggers myself included became columnists, right? So at that point, we have to think much more about who's reading us. There's a lot of people who were writing in public who are now writing privately instead, and it does feel like there's a real loss there. That moment of sort of watching people, trying to figure things out, grapple with them, was a really useful moment. We do this show because we're trying to figure out other ways the internet could work and sort of imagine the internet working very differently."), mdx("p", null, "It feels like Are.na has at least two imaginations. One is this question of an indie web and a question of a web built by individuals and small teams rather than by huge corporations. It has this idea of being a web of ideas, of people thinking in public, instead of sharing these things. Charles, what should we learn from you? How does Are.na help us reimagine the internet and how do you reimagine the internet?"), mdx("p", null, mdx("em", {
